  <static seed="785" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/QuadraticEquations/solveQuad350.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>{100x^{2}+60x+9}=0</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="26" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-3}{10}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>There are a few ways to solve quadratic equations- the easiest way to solve this particular 
type of problem is to use the <em>zero product principle</em>.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
                 {100x^{2}+60x+9}=0 \amp \Rightarrow {\left(10x+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(10x+3\right)}=0 \\
                                    \amp  \Rightarrow {\left\{\frac{-3}{10}\right\}}
       \end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>In this problem there is just <alert>one</alert>, <em>repeated</em> solution.</p>
<p>The solution can be checked by substituting it into the original equation- this is left as an exercise.</p>
</solution>
